vectorData.altText: That's right!  The superior cerebellar artery arises from the side of the BA, near its terminal bifurcation into PCAs.

identify as many of the following arteries as possible.
Identify the superior cerebellar As (E) where they arise from the side of the BA near its terminal bifurcation.
CONTINUING with the wet specimens provided,

Follow them over the superior surface of the cerebellum.  
Identify the anterior inferior cerebellar As (AICAs; F); they arise from the side of the basilar A near its origin at the pontomedullary junction. Follow it over the middle cerebellar peduncle and the anterolateral portions of the inferior surface of the cerebellar hemisphere     . 
Identify the posterior inferior cerebellar As (PICAs; G), if present. They arise from the VAs closer to the spinomedullary junction. Follow the PICAs over the posteriomedial portions of the inferior surface of the cerebellar hemisphere     . 

To summarize, branches of the vertebral-basilar system of arteries are generally responsible for supplying blood to the brainstem, cerebellum, the diencephalon, and the inferior surface and occipital pole of the cerebrum.
if present, emerges between the SCA and the PCA.
Occlusion of the AICA interrupts information flow into the cerebellum through the middle cerebellar peduncle.
The PICA is an important artery clinically.  Occlusion of this vessel results in a great deal of damage to the medulla, and a constellation of signs and symptoms known as Lateral Medullary Syndrome.
